  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;The patient pathway&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I went to Guys Dermatology dept with a friend earlier this month. The appointment letter said to check in in the Welcome area, and then check in again with the receptionist on O1. When we got to the self-check-in machine in the Welcome area, the volunteer there said we shouldn't check in there, and pointed us to the lifts to O, from where we got the lifts to O1. There was no receptionist there, just another self-check-in machine. I think that you should be able to write a form letter, such that it accurately reflects what you want the person attending to do. It should be a simple thing to get right. Someone coming to the hospital (especially the first time) is likely to be a bit stressed and nervous, and if even getting to the waiting area is complicated by being given contradictory instructions, that doesn't help. A further, but related point,  is that patients are directed from where to go from the waiting area by an electronic board, which comes up with the patient's name and the location they should head for, A fairly common location was to the 'Height and Weight area'. Another location was &amp;amp;quot;Touchdown&amp;amp;quot; - goodness knows what that is. There was also a standard message at the bottom of the screen, reminding patients to go to the Check Out area to get their follow-on appointments. However, there were no signs that I could see to show where any of these places might be. Again, it hardly helps patients feel less nervous if they are told to go somewhere they can't find. It probably doesn't help the hospital work efficiently either, if patients don't arrive promptly at wherever it is they have been sent, or have to interrupt staff to find out where to go. Writing appointment letters properly and putting up some signs (or amending the electronic display to be more informative eg &amp;amp;quot;Touchdown on level O&amp;amp;quot;) is not rocket science.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
